{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0109dfd4-fef9-40b1-9595-47d1c3aba0d8","content":"The directory appears empty — there's no project file yet. No worries, here's what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish as a **dotnet tool** on NuGet.org:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<Project Sdk=\"Microsoft.NET.Sdk\">\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n    <TargetFramework>net8.0</TargetFramework>\n\n    <!-- Makes it a dotnet tool -->\n    <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n    <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n    <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n    <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n    <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n    <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n    <Description>An MCP server using stdio transport.</Description>\n    <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</PackageProjectUrl>\n    <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n  </PropertyGroup>\n</Project>\n```\n\n### Key points\n\n| Property | Purpose |\n|----------|---------|\n| `PackAsTool` | Tells `dotnet pack` to produce a tool package |\n| `ToolCommandName` | The CLI command users invoke (e.g., `my-mcp-server`) |\n| `OutputType=Exe` | Required — tools must be executables |\n\n### Publishing steps\n\n```bash\n# 1. Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# 2. Push to NuGet.org (get API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install --global MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server   # runs via stdio\n```\n\nThat's the minimal setup. Want me to create the project file for you?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a119278a-9340-4c49-9976-efd9f4d9c0c2","outputTokens":522,"requestId":"2C00:2ED2CA:290B28E:2D6E262:69FD36CE"},"id":"3568b402-ddcd-4c76-86a2-5a4da2f82838","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:05:28.410Z","parentId":"37be47c8-fb0d-4179-9c5a-c883797e54f9"}
